<section id="education">

<h3>Education</h3>

<article>
<h4>Nottingham Trent University</h4>
<p class="meta">BSc (H) Software Engineering · 2020 – 2023 · 1st Class Honours</p>

<h5 class="section-heading">Key modules</h5>

<div class="module">
<h6>Advanced Analysis &amp; Design (1HIGH)</h6>
<p>
I worked in a team of 7, analysing, designing and developing a smart fridge
system from requirements derived from the problem specification. We went through
the whole software development lifecycle of creating a detailed plan, weekly
meetings, gathering requirements from interviews and research, creating design
documents using UML notation such as use-case and class diagrams. Using the
ASP.NET Razor Pages framework, we developed a piece of software based on our
designs and implemented a test plan of a suite of tests including functional,
unit and acceptance tests.
</p>
<p>See <a href="#future-fridges">Future Fridges</a> in the project section for more information.</p>
</div>

<div class="module">
<h6>Practical Project Management (1HIGH)</h6>
<p>
Working in a team of seven I led the development of an ASP.NET Razor Pages
application that empowered staff members at the charity organisation, Reach
Learning Disability, to create comprehensive step-by-step guides utilising a
blend of video, pictures, and text. The primary objective was to enhance the
independence of service users at their “Flower Pod” site which provides
therapeutic horticulture to individuals with learning disabilities, enabling
them to navigate various tasks with greater ease. The application, accessible
via on-site tablets, featured a text-to-speech functionality, catering to users
with limited reading abilities. For our efforts, we were awarded a First-class
grade.
</p>
</div>

<div class="module">
<h6>Advanced Software Engineering (1HIGH)</h6>
<p>
I studied many data structures such as continuous structures like arrays or
linked structures such as linked lists and binary search trees. I implemented
recursive algorithms over linked data structures such as traversing trees and
inserting/removing/rotating nodes. I analysed algorithms using Big-O notation
based on reasoning how the function will operate in the worst-case scenario. I
used the principles of test-driven development to develop a Dictionary library
class using a BST as the underlying data structure in Haskell and C++.
</p>
</div>
</article>

